# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: albert-gleizes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:albert-gleizes/391-magazine] The title of the magazine derives from Alfred Stieglitz's New York periodical *291* (to which Picabia had contributed), and bore no relation to its contents.
[src:albert-gleizes/391-magazine] Despite Picabia's renown as an artist, it was mostly literary in content, with a wide-ranging aggressive tone, possibly influenced by Alfred Jarry and Guillaume Apollinaire.
[src:albert-gleizes/391-magazine] There were contributions by Marie Laurencin, Man Ray, Georges Ribemont-Dessaignes and Marcel Duchamp.
[src:albert-gleizes/391-magazine] Starting from its fifth issue the magazine was published in New York City.
[src:albert-gleizes/391-magazine] Its eighth issue was published in Zurich.
[src:albert-gleizes/391-magazine] Then the magazine was published in Paris until 1924 when its last issue, number 19, was distributed.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] In mathematics, a **4-manifold** is a 4-dimensional topological manifold.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] A **smooth 4-manifold** is a 4-manifold with a smooth structure.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] In dimension four, in marked contrast with lower dimensions, topological and smooth manifolds are quite different.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] There exist some topological 4-manifolds which admit no smooth structure, and even if there exists a smooth structure, it need not be unique (i.e. there are smooth 4-manifolds which are homeomorphic but not diffeomorphic).
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] 4-manifolds are important in physics because in general relativity, spacetime is modeled as a pseudo-Riemannian 4-manifold.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The homotopy type of a simply connected compact 4-manifold only depends on the intersection form on the middle dimensional homology.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] Freedman's classification can be extended to some cases when the fundamental group is not too complicated; for example, when it is $\mathbb {Z}$ , there is a classification similar to the one above using Hermitian forms over the group ring of $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] If the fundamental group is too large (for example, a free group on 2 generators), then Freedman's techniques seem to fail and very little is known about such manifolds.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] For any finitely presented group it is easy to construct a (smooth) compact 4-manifold with it as its fundamental group.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] This is one reason why much of the work on 4-manifolds just considers the simply connected case: the general case of many problems is already known to be intractable.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] For manifolds of dimension at most 6, any piecewise linear (PL) structure can be smoothed in an essentially unique way, so in particular the theory of 4 dimensional PL manifolds is much the same as the theory of 4 dimensional smooth manifolds.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] A major open problem in the theory of smooth 4-manifolds is to classify the simply connected compact ones.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] Classify the different smooth structures on a smoothable manifold.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] There is an almost complete answer to the first problem asking which simply connected compact 4-manifolds have smooth structures.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] First, the Kirby–Siebenmann class must vanish.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] By contrast, very little is known about the second question of classifying the smooth structures on a smoothable 4-manifold; in fact, there is not a single smoothable 4-manifold where the answer is fully known.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] Donaldson showed that there are some simply connected compact 4-manifolds, such as Dolgachev surfaces, with a countably infinite number of different smooth structures.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] There are an uncountable number of different smooth structures on **R**4; see exotic **R**4.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] Fintushel and Stern showed how to use surgery to construct large numbers of different smooth structures (indexed by arbitrary integral polynomials) on many different manifolds, using Seiberg–Witten invariants to show that the smooth structures are different.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] Their results suggest that any classification of simply connected smooth 4-manifolds will be very complicated.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] There are currently no plausible conjectures about what this classification might look like.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] There are several fundamental theorems about manifolds that can be proved by low-dimensional methods in dimensions at most 3, and by completely different high-dimensional methods in dimension at least 5, but which are false in dimension 4.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] According to Frank Quinn, "Two *n*-dimensional submanifolds of a manifold of dimension 2*n* will usually intersect themselves and each other in isolated points.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The "Whitney trick" uses an isotopy across an embedded 2-disk to simplify these intersections.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] Roughly speaking this reduces the study of *n*-dimensional embeddings to embeddings of 2-disks.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] But this is not a reduction when the dimension is 4: the 2-disks themselves are middle-dimensional, so trying to embed them encounters exactly the same problems they are supposed to solve.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The uniformization theorem for two-dimensional surfaces states that every simply connected Riemann surface can be given one of three geometries (Euclidean, spherical, or hyperbolic).
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] In dimension 3, it is not always possible to assign a geometry to a closed 3-manifold but the resolution of the geometrization conjecture, proposed by William Thurston (1982), implies that closed 3-manifolds can be decomposed into geometric *pieces*.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] In dimension four the situation is more complicated.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] Not every closed 4-manifold can be uniformized by a Lie group or even decomposed into geometrizable pieces.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] This follows from unsolvability of the homeomorphism problem for 4-manifolds.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] But, there is still a classification of 4-dimensional geometries due to Richard Filipkiewicz.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] These fall into 18 distinct geometries and one infinite family.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] An in depth discussion of the geometries and the manifolds that afford them is given in Hillman's book.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The study of complex structures on geometrizable 4-manifolds was initiated by Wall.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The distinction in to the following classes is somewhat arbitrary, the emphasis has been placed on properties of the fundamental group and the uniformizing Lie group.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The classification of the geometries is taken from.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] Three geometries lie here, the 4-sphere $S^{4}$ , the complex projective plane $\mathbf {P} _{\mathbb {C} }^{2}$ , and a product of two 2-spheres $S^{2}\times S^{2}$ .
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The fundamental group of any such manifold is finite.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] This is the four dimensional Euclidean space $\mathbb {E} ^{4}$ .
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] With isometry group $\mathbb {R} ^{4}\rtimes \mathrm {O} (4)$ .
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The fundamental group of any such manifold is a Bieberbach group.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] There are 74 homeomorphism classes of manifolds with geometry $\mathbb {E} ^{4}$ , 27 orientable manifolds and 47 non-orientable manifolds.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] There are two geometries of Nilpotent type $\mathbf {Nil} ^{4}$ and the reducible geometry $\mathbf {Nil} ^{3}\times \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The $\mathbf {Nil} ^{4}$ geometry is a 4-dimensional nilpotent Lie group given as the semi-direct product $\mathbb {R} ^{3}\rtimes _{\Theta }\mathbb {R}$ , where $\Theta (t)=\mathrm {diag} [t,t,{\frac {1}{2}}t^{2}]$ .
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The fundamental group of a closed orientable $\mathbf {Nil} ^{4}$ -manifold is nilpotent of class 3.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] For a closed 4-manifold M admitting a $\mathbf {Nil} ^{3}\times \mathbb {R}$ geometry, there is a finite cover $M'$ of M such that $\pi _{1}M\cong \Gamma \times \mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] Here $\Gamma$ is the fundamental group of a 3-dimensional nilmanifold.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] Thus, every such fundamental group is nilpotent of class 2.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] Note that one can always take $\Gamma$ above to be one of the following groups $\Gamma _{q}:=\langle x,y,z\ |\ xz=zx,\ zy=yz,\ xy=z^{q}yx\rangle$ , where $q\in \mathbb {Z}$ is non-zero.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] These are all fundamental groups of torus bundles over the circle.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] As well as a countably infinite family $\mathbf {Sol} _{m,n}^{4}$ where $m,n\geq 1$ are integers.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The fundamental group of a closed $\mathbf {Sol} _{0}^{4}$ -manifold is a semidirect product $\mathbb {Z} ^{3}\rtimes _{A}\mathbb {Z}$ where $A\in \mathrm {GL} _{3}(\mathbb {Z} )$ has one real eigenvalue and two conjugate complex eigenvalues.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The fundamental group has Hirsh length equal to 4.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] A closed $\mathbf {Sol} _{1}^{4}$ -manifold M is a mapping torus of a $\mathbf {Nil} ^{3}$ -manifold.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] Its fundamental group is a semidirect product $\Gamma _{q}\rtimes \mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] If $m,n$ are positive integers such that $0<2{\sqrt {n}}\leq m<n$ , then $f(x)$ has three distinct real roots $a,b,c$ .
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The fundamental group of a closed $\mathbf {Sol} _{m,n}^{4}$ -manifold is a semidirect product $\mathbb {Z} ^{3}\rtimes _{A}\mathbb {Z}$ where $A\in \mathrm {GL} _{3}(\mathbb {Z} )$ has three distinct real eigenvalues.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] Note that when $n=m$ that $\Theta _{n,n}$ has exactly one eigenvalue.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] So there is an identification $\mathbf {Sol} _{n,n}^{4}=\mathbf {Sol^{3}} \times \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] There are two geometries here real-hyperbolic 4-space $\mathbf {H} _{\mathbb {R} }^{4}$ and the complex hyperbolic plane $\mathbf {H} _{\mathbb {C} }^{2}$ .
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The fundamental groups of closed manifolds here are word hyperbolic groups.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] Closed manifolds come in two forms here.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] A $\mathbf {H} _{\mathbb {R} }^{2}\times \mathbf {H} _{\mathbb {R} }^{2}$ -manifold is *reducible* if it is finitely covered by a direct product of hyperbolic Riemann surfaces.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] The irreducible manifolds fundamental groups are arithmetic groups by Margulis' arithmeticity theorem.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] This geometry admits no closed manifolds.
[src:albert-gleizes/4-manifold] A product of a 3-dimensional geometry with $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] The play consists of several interconnecting plots, connected by a celebration of the wedding of Duke Theseus of Athens and the Amazon queen Hippolyta.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Most of the action occurs in the woodland realm of Fairyland, under the light of the moon.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] The play opens with Theseus and Hippolyta who are four days away from their wedding.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Theseus is unhappy about how long he has to wait while Hippolyta thinks it will pass by like a dream.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Theseus is confronted by Egeus and his daughter Hermia, who is in love with Lysander, and resistant to her father's demand that she marry Demetrius, whom he has arranged for her to marry.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Enraged, Egeus invokes an ancient Athenian law before Duke Theseus, whereby a daughter needs to marry a suitor chosen by her father, or else face death.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Theseus offers her another choice: lifelong chastity as a nun worshipping the goddess Diana, but the two lovers both deny his choice and make a secret plan to escape into the forest for Lysander's aunt's house, to run away from Theseus.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Hermia tells their plans to Helena, her best friend, who pines unrequitedly for Demetrius, who broke up with her to be with Hermia.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Desperate to reclaim Demetrius's love, Helena tells Demetrius about the plan and he follows them in hopes of finding Hermia.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] The mechanicals, Peter Quince and fellow players Nick Bottom, Francis Flute, Robin Starveling, Tom Snout and Snug plan to put on a play for the wedding of the Duke and the Queen, "the most lamentable comedy and most cruel death of Pyramus and Thisbe".
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Quince reads the names of characters and bestows them on the players.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Nick Bottom, who is playing the main role of Pyramus, is over-enthusiastic and wants to dominate others by suggesting himself for the characters of Thisbe, the Lion, and Pyramus at the same time.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Quince insists that Bottom can only play the role of Pyramus.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Bottom would also rather play a tyrant and recites some lines of Ercles.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Bottom is told by Quince that he would play the Lion so terribly as to frighten the duchess and other ladies so much that the Duke and Lords would have the players hanged.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Snug remarks that he needs Lion's part because he is "slow of study".
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Quince assures Snug that the role of the lion is "nothing but roaring." Quince then ends the meeting by telling his actors "At the Duke's oak we meet".
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] In a parallel plot line, at the same time, Oberon, king of the fairies, and Titania, his queen, have come to the forest outside Athens.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Titania tells Oberon that she plans to stay there until she has attended Theseus and Hippolyta's wedding.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Oberon and Titania are estranged because Titania refuses to give her Indian changeling to Oberon for use as his "knight" or "henchman" since the child's mother was one of Titania's worshippers.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] He calls upon Robin "Puck" Goodfellow, his "shrewd and knavish sprite", to help him concoct a magical juice derived from a flower called "love-in-idleness", which turns from white to purple when struck by Cupid's arrow.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] When the concoction is applied to the eyelids of a sleeping person, that person, upon waking, falls in love with the first living thing they perceive.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] He instructs Puck to retrieve the flower with the hope that he might make Titania fall in love with an animal of the forest and thereby shame her into giving up the little Indian boy.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] He says, "And ere I take this charm from off her sight, / As I can take it with another herb, / I'll make her render up her page to me." Helena and Demetrius enter, with her continuously making advances towards Demetrius, promising to love him more than Hermia.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] However, he rebuffs her with cruel insults.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Observing this, Oberon orders Puck to spread some of the magical juice from the flower on the eyelids of the young Athenian man.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] As Titania is lulled to sleep by her fairies, Oberon sneaks up and places the flower juice on her eyes, exiting the stage afterwards.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Lysander and Hermia enter, lost and exhausted from the journey.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Hermia rejects Lysander's advances to sleep together, and the two lie down on different corners.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Puck enters and mistakes Lysander for Demetrius, not having seen either before, and administers the juice to the sleeping Lysander.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Helena, coming across him, wakes him while attempting to determine whether he is dead or asleep.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Upon this happening, Lysander immediately falls in love with Helena.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Helena, mistakenly accusing Lysander of mocking her, runs away.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] When Hermia wakes up after dreaming a snake ate her heart, she sees that Lysander is gone and goes out in the woods to find him.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Meanwhile, Quince and his band of five labourers ("rude mechanicals", as Puck describes them) have arranged to perform their play about Pyramus and Thisbe for Theseus's wedding and venture into the forest, near Titania's bower, for their rehearsal.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Quince leads the actors in their rehearsal of the play.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Bottom is spotted by Puck, who (taking his name to be another word for a jackass) transforms his head into that of a donkey.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] When Bottom returns for his next lines, the other workmen run screaming in terror: They claim that they are haunted, much to Bottom's confusion.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Determined to await his friends, he begins to sing to himself.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Titania, having received the love potion, is awakened by Bottom's singing and immediately falls in love with him.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] (In the words of the play, "Titania waked, and straightway loved an ass.") She lavishes him with her attention and that of her fairies; while she is in this state of devotion, Oberon takes the changeling boy.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Oberon sees Demetrius still following Hermia.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] When Demetrius goes to sleep, Oberon condemns Puck's mistake and sends him to get Helena while he charms Demetrius's eyes.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Upon waking, Demetrius sees Helena arguing with Lysander, and instantly falls in love with her.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Now under the spell, the two men are both in love with a Helena convinced that both of her two suitors are mocking her, as neither loved her originally.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Hermia finds Lysander and asks why he left her, but Lysander claims he never loved Hermia, instead loving Helena.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] This soon turns into a quarrel between the two ladies, with Helena chiding Hermia for joining in the mockery session, followed by the latter furiously charging at her for stealing her true love's heart and blaming her for the supposed 'mockery'.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Oberon and Puck decide that they must resolve this conflict, and by the morning, none of them will have any memory of what happened, as if it were a dream.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Oberon arranges everything so Helena, Hermia, Demetrius, and Lysander will all believe they have been dreaming when they awaken.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Puck distracts Lysander and Demetrius from fighting over Helena's love by mimicking their voices and leading them apart.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Eventually, all four find themselves separately falling asleep in the glade.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Once they fall asleep, Puck administers the antidote to Lysander, returning his love to Hermia again.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Once they awaken, the lovers assume that whatever happened was a dream and not reality.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Having achieved his goals, Oberon releases Titania and orders Puck to remove the donkey's head from Bottom.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] The fairies then disappear, and Theseus and Hippolyta arrive on the scene, during an early morning hunt.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] They find the lovers still sleeping in the glade.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] They wake up the lovers and, since Demetrius no longer loves Hermia, Theseus over-rules Egeus's demands and arranges a group wedding.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] The lovers at first believe they are still in a dream and cannot recall what has happened.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] The lovers decide that the night's events must have been a dream, as they walk back to Athens.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] After they exit, Bottom awakes, and he too decides that he must have experienced a dream "past the wit of man" and declares that he will get Peter Quince to write a Ballad of the previous night's dream.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Fittingly called "Bottom's Dream", Bottom decides that he will sing the ballad after the end of their play, when Thisbe dies.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] At Quince's house, Quince and his team of actors worry that Bottom has gone missing.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Quince laments that Bottom is the only man who can take on the lead role of Pyramus.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Bottom returns and the actors get ready to put on "Pyramus and Thisbe".
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] In the final scene of the play, Theseus, Hippolyta and the lovers watch the six workmen perform *Pyramus and Thisbe* in Athens.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] The mechanicals are so terrible at playing their roles that the guests laugh as if it were meant to be a comedy, and everyone retires to bed.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] Afterwards, Oberon, Titania, Puck, and other fairies enter, and bless the house and its occupants with good fortune.
[src:albert-gleizes/a-midsummer-night-s-dream] After all the other characters leave, Puck "restores amends" and suggests that what the audience experienced might just be a dream.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] In 1905 and early 1906 a group of young artists and poets holding meetings at various locations found that society, the way it was organized, did not take into consideration an environment needed for creative expression, nor the goals it proposed.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] Founded officially in the autumn of 1906 by the painter Albert Gleizes, and the poets René Arcos, Henri-Martin Barzun, Alexandre Mercereau and Charles Vildrac, L'Abbaye de Créteil was a *phalanstère*, a utopian community.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] The movement drew its inspiration from the *Abbaye de Thélème,* a fictional creation by Rabelais in his novel *Gargantua*.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] It was closed down by its members early in 1908.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] Georges Duhamel and Vildrac settled in Créteil, just to the southeast of Paris, in a house in a park-like setting along the river Marne.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] Their aim was to establish a place of freedom and friendship favourable for artistic and literary creativity.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] Henri-Martin Barzun (father of the historian and cultural critic Jacques Barzun) was a financial contributor to his friends at the *Abbaye de Créteil*.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] The group tried to create a publishing house that would bring in sufficient income to support the *Abbaye*.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] The typographer Lucien Linard, a friend of Albert Gleizes, furnished the printing press.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] From January 1907 through January 1908, some twenty books were published by the *Abbaye*.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] Barzun, more sophisticated than the other idealists of the Abbaye, introduced Gleizes to the specific history of Utopian socialism.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] Though Gleizes did not enter the Abbaye with a specific program in mind.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] The art historian Daniel Robbins is responsible for laying out the filiation between the Paul Fort's *Vers et Prose*, the Abbaye, post-Symbolist writers and politically engaged aesthetic thinking that would lead Gleizes to Cubism.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] Robbin's pioneering work brought the history of the Abbaye to an Anglo-American readership.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] He characterized their endeavors as a 'search for a synthetic modern art' that gave expression to social ideas.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] The fame of the Abbaye circulated even in Moscow, attracting many artists along the way.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] Filippo Tommaso Marinetti and Constantin Brâncuși were visitors there and young writers like Roger Allard (one of the first to defend Cubism), Pierre Jean Jouve, and Paul Castiaux are some of the artists who wanted to publish their works through the Abbaye.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] The Abbaye group, in principle supporting themselves through the communal work of publishing, were supported by many Symbolists.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] Yet its members soon began to break with the art forms practiced by the respected older generation.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] Like many Symbolists, the Abbaye artists "scorned the structure of a bourgeois world and sought to substitute a communal society", writes Robbins, "but they did not reject the themes of modern life in favor of the Symbolist focus on single elements and internal, individual images".
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] They wished instead "to create an epic and heroic art, stripped of ornament and obscure allegory", Robbins continues, "an art dealing with the relevant subjects of modern life: crowds, man and machines, even, ultimately, the city itself".
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] The intentions of the Abbaye were vast and would ultimately remain unfulfilled.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] Their goal, like that of the Symbolists before them, was equivalent to an escape from reality.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] "Yet there were important distinctions", write Robbins, "for the Abbaye intention to create a total future a priori ruled out the Symbolist technique of creating solely from an aesthetic or a closed ideal".
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] The *Abbaye* attracted much interest but little revenue and its young members found themselves forced to close their beloved *Abbaye* on January 28, 1908.
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] Its publishing house survived for a while and the friends continued to gather every month for a *dîner des copains* (in French, "dinner of pals").
[src:albert-gleizes/abbaye-de-créteil] Shortly after its dissolution, Gleizes moved to 7 rue du Delta near Montmartre, Paris, with artists Henri Doucet, Amedeo Modigliani, Maurice Drouart and Geo Printemps.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Western art had been, from the Renaissance up to the middle of the 19th century, underpinned by the logic of perspective and an attempt to reproduce an illusion of visible reality.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] By the end of the 19th century, many artists felt a need to create a new kind of art that would encompass the fundamental changes taking place in technology, science, and philosophy.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The sources from which individual artists drew their theoretical arguments were diverse and reflected the social and intellectual preoccupations in all areas of Western culture at that time.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Abstraction indicates a departure from reality in depiction of imagery in art.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] This departure from accurate representation can be slight, partial, or complete.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Artwork which takes liberties, e.g. altering color or form in ways that are conspicuous, can be said to be partially abstract.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Total abstraction bears no trace of any reference to anything recognizable.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] In geometric abstraction, for instance, one is unlikely to find references to naturalistic entities.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Figurative art and total abstraction are almost mutually exclusive.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] But figurative and representational (or realistic) art often contain partial abstraction.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Both geometric abstraction and lyrical abstraction are often totally abstract.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Among the very numerous art movements that embody partial abstraction would be for instance fauvism in which color is conspicuously and deliberately altered vis-a-vis reality, and cubism, which alters the forms of the real-life entities depicted.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] In 19th century Europe, patronage from the church diminished and private patronage from the public became more capable of providing a livelihood for artists.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Three art movements which contributed to the development of abstract art were Romanticism, Impressionism and Expressionism.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Artistic independence for artists was advanced during the 19th century.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] An objective interest in what is seen can be discerned from the paintings of John Constable, J.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Turner, Camille Corot and from them to the Impressionists who continued the *plein air* painting of the Barbizon school.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Early intimations of a new art had been made by James McNeill Whistler who, in his painting *Nocturne in Black and Gold: The Falling Rocket*, (1872), placed greater emphasis on visual sensation than the depiction of objects.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Even earlier than that, with her "spirit" drawings, Georgiana Houghton's choice to work with abstract shapes correlate with the unnatural nature of her subject, in a time when abstraction was not yet a concept (she organized an exhibit in 1871).
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Expressionist painters explored the bold use of paint surface, drawing distortions and exaggerations, and intense color.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Expressionists produced emotionally charged paintings that were reactions to and perceptions of contemporary experience; and reactions to Impressionism and other more conservative directions of late 19th-century painting.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The Expressionists drastically changed the emphasis on subject matter in favor of the portrayal of psychological states of being.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Although artists like Edvard Munch and James Ensor drew influences principally from the work of the Post-Impressionists they were instrumental to the advent of abstraction in the 20th century.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Paul Cézanne had begun as an Impressionist but his aim – to make a logical construction of reality based on a view from a single point, with modulated color in flat areas – became the basis of a new visual art, later to be developed into Cubism.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Additionally in the late 19th century in Eastern Europe mysticism and early modernist religious philosophy as expressed by theosophist Mme.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Blavatsky had a profound impact on pioneer geometric artists like Hilma af Klint and Wassily Kandinsky.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The mystical teaching of Georges Gurdjieff and P.D.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Ouspensky also had an important influence on the early formations of the geometric abstract styles of Piet Mondrian and his colleagues in the early 20th century.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The spiritualism also inspired the abstract art of Kasimir Malevich and František Kupka.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The raw language of color as developed by the Fauves directly influenced another pioneer of abstraction, Wassily Kandinsky.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Cubism, based on Cézanne's idea that all depiction of nature can be reduced to cube, sphere and cone became, along with Fauvism, the art movement that directly opened the door to abstraction in the early 20th century.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] During the 1912 Salon de la Section d'Or, where František Kupka exhibited his abstract painting *Amorpha, Fugue en deux couleurs* (*Fugue in Two Colors*) (1912), the poet Guillaume Apollinaire named the work of several artists including Robert Delaunay, *Orphism*.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Since the turn of the century, cultural connections between artists of the major European cities had become extremely active as they strove to create an art form equal to the high aspirations of modernism.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Ideas were able to cross-fertilize by means of artist's books, exhibitions and manifestos so that many sources were open to experimentation and discussion, and formed a basis for a diversity of modes of abstraction.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] During the Spring David Burliuk gave two lectures on cubism and planned a polemical publication, which the Knave of Diamonds was to finance.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] He went abroad in May and came back determined to rival the almanac *Der Blaue Reiter* which had emerged from the printers while he was in Germany".
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] From 1909 to 1913 many experimental works in the search for this 'pure art' had been created by a number of artists: Francis Picabia painted *Caoutchouc*, c.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] With his expressive use of color and his free and imaginative drawing, Henri Matisse comes very close to pure abstraction in *French Window at Collioure* (1914), *View of Notre-Dame* (1914), and *The Yellow Curtain* from 1915.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] And the search continued: The Rayist (Luchizm) drawings of Natalia Goncharova and Mikhail Larionov, used lines like rays of light to make a construction.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Kasimir Malevich completed his first entirely abstract work, the Suprematist, *Black Square*, in 1915.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Another of the Suprematist group' Liubov Popova, created the Architectonic Constructions and Spatial Force Constructions between 1916 and 1921.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Piet Mondrian was evolving his abstract language, of horizontal and vertical lines with rectangles of color, between 1915 and 1919, Neo-Plasticism was the aesthetic which Mondrian, Theo van Doesburg and other in the group De Stijl intended to reshape the environment of the future.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Many of the abstract artists in Russia became Constructivists believing that art was no longer something remote, but life itself.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The artist must become a technician, learning to use the tools and materials of modern production.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] *Art into life!* was Vladimir Tatlin's slogan, and that of all the future Constructivists.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Varvara Stepanova and Alexandre Exter and others abandoned easel painting and diverted their energies to theatre design and graphic works.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] On the other side stood Kazimir Malevich, Anton Pevsner and Naum Gabo.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] They argued that art was essentially a spiritual activity; to create the individual's place in the world, not to organize life in a practical, materialistic sense.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] During that time, representatives of the Russian avant-garde collaborated with other Eastern European Constructivist artists, including Władysław Strzemiński, Katarzyna Kobro, and Henryk Stażewski.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Many of those who were hostile to the materialist production idea of art left Russia.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Anton Pevsner went to France, Gabo went first to Berlin, then to England and finally to America.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Kandinsky studied in Moscow then left for the Bauhaus.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] By the mid-1920s the revolutionary period (1917 to 1921) when artists had been free to experiment was over; and by the 1930s only socialist realism was allowed.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] As visual art becomes more abstract, it develops some characteristics of music: an art form which uses the abstract elements of sound and divisions of time.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Wassily Kandinsky, himself an amateur musician, was inspired by the possibility of marks and associative color *resounding in the soul.* The idea had been put forward by Charles Baudelaire, that all our senses respond to various stimuli but the senses are connected at a deeper aesthetic level.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Closely related to this, is the idea that art has *The spiritual dimension* and can transcend 'every-day' experience, reaching a spiritual plane.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The Theosophical Society popularized the ancient wisdom of the sacred books of India and China in the early years of the century.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] It was in this context that Piet Mondrian, Wassily Kandinsky, Hilma af Klint and other artists working towards an 'objectless state' became interested in the occult as a way of creating an 'inner' object.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The universal and timeless shapes found in geometry: the circle, square and triangle become the spatial elements in abstract art; they are, like color, fundamental systems underlying visible reality.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The Bauhaus at Weimar, Germany was founded in 1919 by Walter Gropius.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The philosophy underlying the teaching program was unity of all the visual and plastic arts from architecture and painting to weaving and stained glass.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] This philosophy had grown from the ideas of the Arts and Crafts movement in England and the Deutscher Werkbund.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Among the teachers were Paul Klee, Wassily Kandinsky, Johannes Itten, Josef Albers, Anni Albers, and László Moholy-Nagy.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] In 1925 the school was moved to Dessau and, as the Nazi party gained control in 1932, The Bauhaus was closed.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] In 1937 an exhibition of degenerate art, 'Entartete Kunst' contained all types of avant-garde art disapproved of by the Nazi party.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Then the exodus began: not just from the Bauhaus but from Europe in general; to Paris, London and America.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Paul Klee went to Switzerland but many of the artists at the Bauhaus went to America.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] During the 1930s Paris became the host to artists from Russia, Germany, the Netherlands and other European countries affected by the rise of totalitarianism.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Sophie Tauber and Jean Arp collaborated on paintings and sculpture using organic/geometric forms.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The Polish Katarzyna Kobro applied mathematically based ideas to sculpture.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The many types of abstraction now in close proximity led to attempts by artists to analyse the various conceptual and aesthetic groupings.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] An exhibition by forty-six members of the Cercle et Carré group organized by Joaquín Torres-García assisted by Michel Seuphor contained work by the Neo-Plasticists as well as abstractionists as varied as Kandinsky, Anton Pevsner and Kurt Schwitters.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Criticized by Theo van Doesburg to be too indefinite a collection he published the journal *Art Concret* setting out a manifesto defining an abstract art in which the line, color and surface only are the concrete reality.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Abstraction-Création founded in 1931 as a more open group, provided a point of reference for abstract artists, as the political situation worsened in 1935, and artists again regrouped, many in London.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The first exhibition of British abstract art was held in England in 1935.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The following year the more international *Abstract and Concrete* exhibition was organized by Nicolete Gray including work by Piet Mondrian, Joan Miró, Barbara Hepworth and Ben Nicholson.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Hepworth, Nicholson and Gabo moved to the St.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Ives in Cornwall to continue their constructivist work.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] During the Nazi rise to power in the 1930s many artists fled Europe to the United States.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The rich cultural influences brought by the European artists were distilled and built upon by local New York painters.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The climate of freedom in New York allowed all of these influences to flourish.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The art galleries that primarily had focused on European art began to notice the local art community and the work of younger American artists who had begun to mature.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Certain artists at this time became distinctly abstract in their mature work.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] During this period Piet Mondrian's painting *Composition No.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] 10*, 1939–1942, characterized by primary colors, white ground and black grid lines clearly defined his radical but classical approach to the rectangle and abstract art in general.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Some artists of the period defied categorization, such as Georgia O'Keeffe who, while a modernist abstractionist, was a pure maverick in that she painted highly abstract forms while not joining any specific group of the period.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Eventually American artists who were working in a great diversity of styles began to coalesce into cohesive stylistic groups.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The best-known group of American artists became known as the Abstract expressionists and the New York School.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] In New York City there was an atmosphere which encouraged discussion and there was a new opportunity for learning and growing.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Graham and Hans Hofmann became important bridge figures between the newly arrived European Modernists and the younger American artists coming of age.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Mark Rothko, born in Russia, began with strongly surrealist imagery which later dissolved into his powerful color compositions of the early 1950s.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The expressionistic gesture and the act of painting itself, became of primary importance to Jackson Pollock, Robert Motherwell, and Franz Kline.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] While during the 1940s Arshile Gorky's and Willem de Kooning's figurative work evolved into abstraction by the end of the decade.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] New York City became the center, and artists worldwide gravitated towards it; from other places in America as well.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Digital art, hard-edge painting, geometric abstraction, minimalism, lyrical abstraction, op art, abstract expressionism, color field painting, monochrome painting, assemblage, neo-Dada, shaped canvas painting, are a few directions relating to abstraction in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] In the United States, *Art as Object* as seen in the Minimalist sculpture of Donald Judd and the paintings of Frank Stella are seen today as newer permutations.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Other examples include Lyrical Abstraction and the sensuous use of color seen in the work of painters as diverse as Robert Motherwell, Patrick Heron, Kenneth Noland, Sam Francis, Cy Twombly, Richard Diebenkorn, Helen Frankenthaler, Joan Mitchell, and Veronica Ruiz de Velasco.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] One socio-historical explanation that has been offered for the growing prevalence of the abstract in modern art—an explanation linked to the name of Theodor W.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Adorno—is that such abstraction is a response to (and a reflection of) the growing abstraction of social relations in industrial society.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] Frederic Jameson similarly sees modernist abstraction as a function of the abstract power of money, equating all things equally as exchange-values.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] The social content of abstract art is then precisely the abstract nature of social existence—legal formalities, bureaucratic impersonalization, information/power—in the world of late modernity.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstract-art] By contrast, Post-Jungians would see the quantum theories with their disintegration of conventional ideas of form and matter as underlying the divorce of the concrete and the abstract in modern art.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstraction-création] Founders Theo van Doesburg, Auguste Herbin, Jean Hélion and Georges Vantongerloo started the group to foster abstract art after the trend turned to representation in the 1920s.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstraction-création] Five *Cahiers* (yearbooks) were published between 1932 and 1936 entitled *Abstraction-création: Art non-figuratif*; a reprint edition of the *Cahiers* was published by the Arno Press, New York in 1968.
[src:albert-gleizes/abstraction-création] Art exhibitions were also held throughout Europe.
[src:albert-gleizes/académie-moderne] The **Académie Moderne**, formerly known as **Académie Léger–Ozenfant**, was a free art school in Paris.
[src:albert-gleizes/académie-moderne] It was founded by Fernand Léger and Amédée Ozenfant in 1924.
[src:albert-gleizes/académie-moderne] The school attracted students from Europe and America.
[src:albert-gleizes/académie-moderne] Both Léger and Ozenfant taught there, along with Aleksandra Ekster, Otte Sköld, and Marie Laurencin.
[src:albert-gleizes/académie-moderne] Notable students included Tarsila do Amaral, Florence Henri, Blanche Lazzell, Nadia Khodasevich Léger, and Clay Spohn.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Born Albert Léon Gleizes and raised in Paris, he was the son of a fabric designer who ran a large industrial design workshop.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] He was also the nephew of Léon Comerre, a successful portrait painter who won the 1875 Prix de Rome.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The young Albert Gleizes did not like school and often skipped classes to idle away the time writing poetry and wandering through the nearby Montmartre cemetery.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Finally, after completing his secondary schooling, Gleizes spent four years in the 72nd Infantry Regiment of the French army (Abbeville, Picardie) then began pursuing a career as a painter.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes began to paint self-taught around 1901 in the Impressionist tradition.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] His first landscapes from around Courbevoie appear particularly inspired by Alfred Sisley or Camille Pissarro.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Although clearly related to Pissarro in technique, Gleizes' particular view-points as well as the composition and conception of early works represent a clear departure from the style of late Impressionism.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The density with which these works are painted and their solid framework suggest affinities with Divisionism which were often noted by early critics.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes was only twenty-one years of age when his work titled *La Seine à Asnières* was exhibited at the Société Nationale des Beaux-Arts in 1902.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The following year Gleizes exhibited two paintings at the Salon d'Automne.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In 1905 Gleizes was among the founders of *l'Association Ernest-Renan*, a union of students opposed to military propaganda.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes was in charge of the *Section littéraire et artistique*, organizing theater productions and poetry readings.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] At the Musée des Beaux-Arts de Lyon (Salon de la Société Nationale des Beaux-Arts, 1906), Gleizes exhibited *Jour de marché en banlieue*.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Tending towards 1907 his work evolved into a Post-Impressionist style with strong Naturalist and Symbolist components.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes and others decided to create an *association fraternelle d'artistes* and rent a large house in Créteil.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The Abbaye de Créteil was a self-supporting community of artists that aimed to develop their art free of any commercial concerns.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] For nearly a year, Gleizes along with other painters, poets, musicians and writers, gathered to create.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] A lack of income forced them to give up their cherished Abbaye de Créteil in early 1908 and Gleizes moved to 7 rue du Delta near Montmartre, Paris, with artists Amedeo Modigliani, Henri Doucet, Maurice Drouart and Geo Printemps.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In 1908 Gleizes exhibited at the *Toison d'Or* in Moscow.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The same year, showing a great interest in color and reflecting the transient influence of Fauvism, the work of Gleizes became more synthetic with a proto-Cubist component.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes' Fauve-like period was very brief, lasting several months, and even when his paint was thickest and color brightest, his concern for structural rhythms and simplification was dominant.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] His geometric simplifications at this time were more akin to Pont-Aven School and Les Nabis principles than to Paul Cézanne.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] His landscapes of 1909 are characterized by the reducing of forms of nature to primary shapes.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] During the summer of the same year his style became linear and stripped, broken down into multiple forms and facets with attenuated colors, close to that of the painter Henri Le Fauconnier.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In 1910 a group began to form which included Gleizes, Metzinger, Fernand Léger and Robert Delaunay.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] They met regularly at Henri le Fauconnier's studio on rue Notre-Dame-des-Champs, near the Boulevard de Montparnasse.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] These soirées would often included writers such as Guillaume Apollinaire, Roger Allard, René Arcos, Paul Fort, Pierre-Jean Jouve, Alexandre Mercereau, Jules Romains and André Salmon.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Together with other young painters, the group wanted to emphasise a research into form, in opposition to the Neo-Impressionist emphasis on color.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] From 1910 onwards, Albert Gleizes was directly involved with Cubism, both as an artist and a principal theorist of the movement.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes' involvement in Cubism saw him exhibit at the twenty-sixth Salon des Indépendants in 1910.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] He showed his *Portrait de René Arcos* and *L'Arbre*, two paintings in which the emphasis on simplified form had already begun to overwhelm the representational interest of the paintings.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The same tendency is evident in Jean Metzinger's *Portrait of Apollinaire* in the same Salon.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes exhibited at the 1910 Salon d'Automne with the same artists, followed by the first organized group showing by Cubists, in *Salle 41* of the 1911 Salon des Indépendants (*La Femme aux Phlox (Woman with Phlox)*) together with Metzinger, Delaunay, Le Fauconnier and Léger.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The result was a public scandal which brought Cubism for the first time to the attention of the general public (in contrast, Picasso and Braque were exhibiting in a private gallery and selling to a small circle of connoisseurs).
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] … Metzinger himself painted nudes thatlook like puzzles, the pieces of which are cubes of various sizes; F.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] A talented artist, Albert Gleizes, also allowed himself to try a trianguliste representation of the human figure.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] At the 1911 Salon d'Automne (room 8), Gleizes exhibited his *Portrait de Jacques Nayral* and *La Chasse (The Hunt)*, with, in addition to the group of *Salle 41*, André Lhote, Marcel Duchamp, Jacques Villon, Roger de La Fresnaye and André Dunoyer de Segonzac.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In the fall of that year, though the intermediary of Apollinaire, he met Pablo Picasso for the first time and joined the Puteaux Group which held meetings in the studio of Jacques Villon (Gaston Duchamp) and also included Villon's brothers, Raymond Duchamp-Villon and Marcel Duchamp, amongst others.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Many of these artists also frequented the cafés Le Dôme, La Closerie des Lilas, La Rotonde, Le Select, and La Coupole in Montparnasse.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes exhibited his *Les Baigneuses (The Bathers)* at the 1912 Salon des Indépendants; a show marked by Marcel Duchamp's *Nude Descending a Staircase, No.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] 2*, which itself caused a scandal even amongst the Cubists (Duchamp removed the painting before the opening of the exhibition).
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] This was followed by a group show at the Galeries Dalmau in Barcelona, the first exhibition of Cubism in Spain, another exhibit in Moscow (Valet de Carreau), the Salon de la Société Normande in Rouen, and the Salon de la Section d'Or, October 1912 at the Galerie de la Boétie in Paris.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] This technique of relative motion is pushed to its highest degree of complexity in the monumental *Le Dépiquage des Moissons (Harvest Threshing)* (1912).
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] This ambitious work, with Delaunay's *La Ville de Paris* (*City of Paris*), is one of the largest paintings in the history of Cubism.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] At the Salon d'Automne of 1912 Gleizes exhibited *L'Homme au Balcon (Man on a Balcony)*, now at the Philadelphia Museum of Art.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The Cubist contribution to the 1912 Salon d'Automne created a controversy in the Municipal Council of Paris, leading to a debate in the Chambre des Députés about the use of public funds to provide the venue for such barbaric art.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The Cubists were defended by the Socialist deputy, Marcel Sembat.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Albert Gleizes and Jean Metzinger, in preparation for the Salon de la Section d'Or, published a major defence of Cubism, resulting in the first theoretical essay on the new movement, entitled *Du "Cubisme"* (published by Eugène Figuière in 1912, translated to English and Russian in 1913).
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The essential was in the understanding of space other than by the classical method of perspective; an understanding that would include and integrate the fourth dimension.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Cubism, with its new geometry, its dynamism and multiple view-point perspective, not only represented a departure from Euclid's model, but it achieved, according to Gleizes and Metzinger, a better representation of the real world: one that was mobile and changing in time.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] For Gleizes, Cubism represented a "*normal evolution of an art that was mobile like life itself*." In contrast to Picasso and Braque, Gleizes' intent was not to analyze and describe visual reality.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes had argued that we cannot know the external world, we can only know our *sensations*.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Objects from daily life⎯guitar, pipe or bowl of fruit⎯ did not satisfy his complex idealistic concepts of the physical world.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] His subjects were of vast scale and of provocative social and cultural meaning.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes' intent was to reconstitute and synthesize the real world according to his individual consciousness (*sensations*), through the use of volumes to convey the solidity and structure of objects.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Their weight, placement and effects upon each other, and the inseparability of form and color, was one of the principal lessons of Cézanne.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Forms were simplified and distorted, each shape and color modified by another, rather than splintered.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] His concern was to establish weight, density and volumetric relationships among sections of a broad subject.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes himself characterized the 1910–11 phase of his work as an "analysis of volume relationships," though it bears little relation to the traditional use of the word "analytical" in our understanding of Cubism.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] A central theme of *Du "Cubisme"* was that access to the true essence of the world could be gained by *sensations* alone.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The sensation offered by classical painting was very limited: to only one point of view, from a single point in space and frozen in time.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] But the real world is mobile, both spatially and temporally.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Classical perspective and the formulations of Euclidean geometry were only *conventions* (to use Poincaré's term) that distance us from the truth of our sensations, from the truth of our own human nature.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Man sees the world of natural phenomena from a multitude of angles that form a continuum of sensations in perpetual and continuous change.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The Cubists' aim was to completely eschew absolute space and time in favor of relative motion, to grasp through sensory appearances and translate onto a flat canvas the dynamical properties of the four-dimensional manifold (the natural world).
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Only then could one achieve a better representation of the mobile reality of our living experience.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] If Gleizes and Metzinger write in Du "Cubisme" that we can only know our sensations, it is not because they wish to disregard them, but, on the contrary, to understand them more deeply as the primary source for their own work.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In February 1913, Gleizes and other artists introduced the new style of European modern art to an American audience at the Armory Show (International Exhibition of Modern Art) in New York City, Chicago and Boston.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In addition to *Man on a balcony (l'Homme au Balcon)* no.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] 196, Gleizes exhibited at the Armory Show his 1910 *Femme aux Phlox (Woman with Phlox)*, Museum of Fine Arts, Houston.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes published an article in Ricciotto Canudo's *Montjoie!* entitled "Cubisme et la tradition".
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] It was through the intermediary of Canudo that Gleizes would meet the artist Juliette Roche; a childhood friend of Jean Cocteau and daughter of Jules Roche, an influential politician of the 3rd Republic.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] With the outbreak of World War I, Albert Gleizes re-enlisted in the French army.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] He was put in charge of organizing entertainment for the troops and as a result was approached by Jean Cocteau to design the set and costumes for the William Shakespeare play, *A Midsummer Night's Dream*, along with Georges Valmier.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Discharged from the military in the fall of 1915, Gleizes and his new wife, Juliette Roche, moved to New York, where they would meet regularly with Francis Picabia, Man Ray, Marcel Duchamp and Jean Crotti (who would eventually marry Suzanne Duchamp).
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] It is at this time that Gleizes witnessed, with a critical eye, the readymades of Marcel Duchamp.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] After a short stay at the Albemarle Hotel Gleizes and his wife settled at 103 West Street, where Gleizes painted a series of works inspired by jazz music, skyscrapers, luminous signs and the Brooklyn Bridge.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] From New York City, the couple sailed to Barcelona where they were joined by Marie Laurencin, Francis Picabia and his wife.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The group spent the summer painting at the resort area of Tossa de Mar and in November Gleizes opened his first solo exhibition, at the Galeries Dalmau in Barcelona, 29 November – 12 December 1916.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Returning to New York city in 1917, Gleizes began writing poetic sketches in verse and in prose, some of which were published in Picabia's Dada periodical 391.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Both Gleizes and his wife traveled from New York to Bermuda in September 1917, where he painted a number of landscapes.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] When the war in Europe ended they returned to France where his career evolved more towards teaching through writing and he became involved with the committee of the *Unions Intellectuelles Françaises*.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Although Gleizes did not join the Church until 1941, his next twenty-five years were spent in a logical effort not only to find God but also to have faith.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] By 1919 the pre-war sense of the Cubist movement had been virtually shattered.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Paris was overshadowed by a strong reaction against those visions of common effort and revolutionary construction which Gleizes continued to embrace, while the avant-garde was characterized by the anarchic and, to him, destructive spirit of Dada.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Neither alternative held any appeal for him and, with the Salons dominated by a return to classicism, his old hostility to Paris was constantly nourished.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes' attempt to resuscitate the spirit of the Section d'Or was met with great difficulty, despite support by Alexander Archipenko, Georges Braque and Léopold Survage.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] His own organizational efforts were directed towards the re-establishment of a European-wide movement of abstract artists in the form of a large travelling exhibition, the *Exposition de la Section d’Or*, in 1920; it was not the success he had hoped for.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Cubism was passé for younger artists, although Gleizes, on the contrary, felt that only its preliminary phase had been investigated.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] It was the revival of the Section d'Or which ensured that Cubism in general and Gleizes in particular would become Dada's preferred target.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Similarly, an effort to organize an artists' cooperative received the support of Robert Delaunay, but of no other major artists.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes was in nearly every sense a maverick Cubist, perhaps the most unyielding of them all; both in his paintings and writings (which had a big impact on the image of Cubism in Europe and the United States).
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] He developed a single-minded, thoroughly uncompromising Cubism without the diversion of a classical alternative.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] During the 1920s Gleizes worked on a highly abstract brand of Cubism.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In addition to his shows at Léonce Rosenberg's L'Effort Moderne, the dealer-publisher Povolozky printed his writings.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] His art was indeed backed by a prodigious theoretical effluence, most notably in *La Peinture et ses lois* (first published in *La Vie des Lettres*, October 1922).
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes fused aesthetic, metaphysical, moral and social priorities to describe the status and function of art.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In *La Peinture et ses lois* writes Robbins, "Gleizes deduced the rules of painting from the picture plane, its proportions, the movement of the human eye and the laws of the universe.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Diagrams entitled "*Simultaneous movements of rotation and shifting of the plane on its axis*" were published to illustrate the concept.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] One of Gleizes's primary objectives was to answer the questions: How will the planar surface be animated, and by what logical method, independent of the artists *fantaisie*, can it be attained?
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Continuing, Gleizes states that the 'reality' of a painting is not that of a mirror, but of the object... issue of imminent logic (p.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] 'The subject-pretext tending toward numeration, inscribed following the nature of the plane, attains a tangent intersections between known images of the natural world and unknown images that reside within intuition' (p.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The problem set out by Gleizes was to replace *anecdote* as a starting point for the work of art, by the sole means of using the elements of the painting itself: line, form and color.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] (2) By displacement of the initial form; pivoting around an imaginary axis in one direction or another.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The choice of position (through translation and/or rotation), though based on the inspiration of the artist, is no longer attributed to the anecdotal.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] An objective and rigorous method, independent of the painter, replaces emotion or sensibility in the determination the placement of form, that is through *translation* and *rotation*.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Space and rhythm, according to Gleizes, are perceptible by the extent of movement (displacement) of planar surfaces.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] These elemental transformations modify the position and importance of the initial plane, whether they converge or diverge ('recede' or 'advance') from the eye, creating a series of new and separate spatial planes appreciable physiologically by the observer.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Another movement is added to the first movement of translation of the plane to one side: Rotation of the plane.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] I shows the resulting formation that follows from simultaneous movements of rotation and translation of the initial plane produced on the axis.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] III represent the simultaneous movements of rotation and translation of the rectangle, inclined to the right and to the left.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The axis point at which movement is realized is established by the observer.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] IV represents the simultaneous movements of rotation and translation of the rectangle plane, with the position of the eye of the observed displaced left of the axis.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Displacement toward the right (though not represented) is straightforward enough to imagine.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] With these figures Gleizes attempts to present, under the most simple conditions possible (simultaneous movements of rotation and translation of the plane), the creation of a spatial and rhythmic organism (Fig.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] VIII), with practically no initiative taken on the part of the artist who controls the evolutionary process.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] VIII are filled with hatching espousing the 'direction' of the planes.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] What emerges in the inert plane, according to Gleizes, through the movement followed by the eye of the observer, is "a visible imprint of successive stages of which the initial rhythmic cadence coordinated a succession of differing states".
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] These successive stages permit the perception of space.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The initial state, by consequence of the transformation, has become a spatial and rhythmic organism.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] II obtain mechanically, Gleizes writes, with minimal personal initiative, a "plastic spatial and rhythmic system", by the conjugation of simultaneous movements of rotation and translation of the plane and from the movements of translation of the plane to one side.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The result is a spatial and rhythmic organism more *complex* than shown in Fig.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] VIII; demonstrating through mechanical, purely plastic means, the realization of a material universe independent of intentional intervention by the artist.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes' painting of 1920–1922, submitted to the same rigor, were not Cubist in any conventional sense; but they *were* Cubist in their concern with planimetric space, and in their relationship (synthesis) with subject-matter.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Indeed, the abstract appearance of these compositions is misleading.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes had always remained committed to synthesis.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] He described how artists had freed themselves from the 'subject-image' as a pretext to work from the 'subjectless-image' (nebulous forms) until they came together.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The images known from the natural world combined with those nebulous forms were made 'spiritually human'.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Though Gleizes considered his works as initially nonrepresentational and only afterwards as denotational.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Before World War I, Gleizes had always been identified as a Cubist avant-garde.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] And during the twenties he continued to hold a prominent position, but he was no longer identified with the avant-garde since Cubism had been superseded by Dada and Surrealism.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Even after historians began their attempts to analyze the vital role played by Cubism, the name of Albert Gleizes was always mentioned because of his early and important participation in the movement.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes had never ceased to call himself a Cubist and theoretically a Cubist he remained.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In many ways his theories were close to those developed by Mondrian, though his paintings never submitted to the discipline of primary colors and the right angle; they were not Neo-Plastic (or De Stijl) in character.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In fact, his works from the late 1920s through the 1940s looked like nothing else that was being done, and indeed, they were rarely seen in the art world because Gleizes deliberately distanced himself from extensive participation in the Parisian scene.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes realized that his evolution towards 'purity' carried with it the risk of alienation from the 'mentality of the milieu', but he saw it as the sole means of arriving at a new type of art that could reach a mass audience (just as the French murals of the 11th and 12th centuries).
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In *Du Cubisme et les moyens de comprendre* (1920), Gleizes went so far as to envisage the mass-production of painting; as a means of undermining the market system and thus the status of artworks as commodities.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] After World War I, with the support given by the dealer Léonce Rosenberg, Cubism returned as a central issue for artists.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes' organizational efforts were directed towards the establishment of a European-wide movement of Cubist and abstract art in the form of a large traveling exhibition; the *Exposition de la Section d’Or*.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The idea was to bring together a collection of works that revealed the complete process of transformation and renewal that had taken place.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] It was not the success he had hoped for.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Cubism was seen as passé for emerging artists and other established artists such as Marcel Duchamp and Picabia, although Gleizes, on the contrary, felt that only its preliminary phase had been investigated.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In addition to Cubists works (which already represented a wide variety of styles), the second edition of the Section d'Or held at the Galerie La Boétie from 5 March 1920 included De Stijl, Bauhaus, Constructivism and Futurism.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] It was the revival of the Section d'Or which ensured that Cubism in general would become Dada's preferred target.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The new polemic resulted in the publication of *Du cubisme et des moyens de le comprendre* by Gleizes, followed in 1922 by *La Peinture et ses lois*.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Following the death of Jules Roche, the Gleizes' had enough independent income and real estate to pursue their goals without bowing to material considerations, unlike many other artists.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The Gleizes' spent more and more time at the family home in Serrières, in Cavalaire, and an even quieter location on the French Riviera, both associating with people more sympathetic to their social ideas.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes became active in the *Union Intellectuelle* and lectured extensively in France, Germany, Poland and England, while continuing to write.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In 1924–25 the Bauhaus (where certain ideals analogous to his own were practiced) requested a new book on Cubism (as part of a series which included Wassily Kandinsky's *Point and Line to Plane*, Paul Klee's *Pedagogical Notebooks*, and Kasimir Malevich's *The Non-Objective World*).
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes, in response, would write *Kubismus* (published in 1928) for the collection of Bauhausbücher 13, Munich.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The publication of Kubismus in French the following year would bring Gleizes closer to Delaunay.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In 1924 Gleizes, Léger and Amédée Ozenfant opened *Académie Moderne*.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In 1927, still dreaming of the communal days at the Abbaye de Créteil, Gleizes founded an artist's colony at a rented house called the *Moly-Sabata* in Sablons near his wife's family home in Serrières in the Ardèche département in the Rhône Valley.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Léonce Rosenberg, in 1929, commissioned Gleizes (replacing Gino Severini) to paint decorative panels for his Parisian residence, which would be installed in 1931.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The same year Gleizes was part of the committee of Abstraction-Création (founded by Theo van Doesburg, Auguste Herbin, Jean Hélion and Georges Vantongerloo) that acted as a forum for international non-representational art, and counteracted the influence of the Surrealist group led by André Breton.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] By this time, his work reflected the strengthening of his religious convictions and his 1932 book, *Vers une conscience plastique, La Forme et l’histoire* examines Celtic, Romanesque, and Oriental art.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] On tour in Poland and Germany, he gave lectures titled *Art et Religion, Art et Production* and *Art et Science* and wrote a book on Robert Delaunay but it was never published.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] The level of 'translation' is generally a geometrical figure evoking a representational image, unlike the work of the early 1930s.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] These works no longer articulate the strict non-representation of *Abstraction Création*.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Léonce Rosenberg—who had already published Gleizes extensively in his *Bulletin de l'Effort Moderne*, but had not previously shown much enthusiasm for his painting—was deeply impressed by Gleizes' paintings (which followed from his 1934 research) at the Salon d'Automne.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] This was the beginning of a close relationship with Gleizes, which continued through the 1930s and is reflected in a stream of correspondence.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In 1937, Gleizes was commissioned to paint murals for the Exposition Internationale des Arts et Techniques dans la Vie Moderne at the Paris World's Fair.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] He collaborated with the Delaunays in the *Pavillon de l'Air* and with Léopold Survage and Fernand Léger for the *Pavillon de l'Union des Artistes Modernes*.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] At the end of 1938, Gleizes volunteered to participate in the free seminars and discussion groups for young painters set up by Robert Delaunay at his Paris studio.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Other examples of this ambitious public style include *The Transfiguration* (1939–41; Lyon, Mus.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In the late 1930s, the wealthy American art connoisseur Peggy Guggenheim purchased a great deal of the new art in Paris including works by Albert Gleizes.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] She brought these works to the United States which today form part of the Peggy Guggenheim Collection.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Albert Gleizes did believe in the Roman catholic church and even considered himself a catholic dating back to the 1920s.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Despite his admiration for the Western Christian tradition and the early medieval church, Gleizes did not join the Roman Catholic Church until 1941.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes believed that the church had lost its "spirit" since the rise of scholastic philosophy and representational art in the thirteenth century.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] However, in 1941, he soon came to believe that the sacraments were still true and effective, despite some intellectual deviations.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In 1942, he was formally confirmed into the Roman Catholic Church and received his First Communion.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] After joining the Church, Gleizes would write memoirs and series that talked about meditation such as "Supports de contemplation" and "Souvenirs: Le Cubisme" adding on Large Triptychs.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] A retrospective of Gleizes'artwork was held at the Chapelle du Lycée Ampère in Lyon in 1947, marking the end of his career.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Gleizes' last creations include a set of 57 illustrations for Blaise Pascal's Pensées, and a fresco called The Eucharist which was located in a chapel at a new Jesuit seminary in the Fontaines community in Chantilly.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] During World War II, Gleizes and his wife remained in France under the German occupation.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In 1942 Gleizes began the series of *Supports de Contemplation*, large scale, entirely non-representational paintings that are both very complex and very serene.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Materials being difficult to obtain during the war, Gleizes painted on burlap, sizing the porous material with a mixture of glue and paint.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] He had used burlap in some of his earliest paintings and now found it favorable to his vigorous touch, for it took the most powerful strokes even while preserving the matte surface he so valued.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In 1952, Gleizes realized his last major work, a fresco titled *Eucharist* that he painted for a Jesuit chapel in Chantilly.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Albert Gleizes died in Avignon in the Vaucluse département on 23 June 1953 and was interred in his wife's family mausoleum in the cemetery at Serrières.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] In celebration of the 100th anniversary of the publication of *Du "Cubisme"* by Albert Gleizes and Jean Metzinger, the Musée de La Poste in Paris presented a show entitled *Gleizes – Metzinger.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Du cubisme et après*, from 9 May to 22 September 2012.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] Over 80 paintings and drawings, along with documents, films and 15 works by other members of the Section d'Or group (Villon, Duchamp-Villon, Kupka, Le Fauconnier, Lhote, La Fresnaye, Survage, Herbin, Marcoussis, Archipenko...) were included in the show.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] A catalogue in French and English was published for the event.
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] A French postage stamp is issued representing works by Gleizes (*Le Chant de Guerre*, 1915) and Metzinger (*L'Oiseau Bleu*, 1913).
[src:albert-gleizes/albert-gleizes-p01] This is the first time that a museum has organized an exhibit showcasing both Gleizes and Metzinger together.
